 <p><img src=http://web4.facelink.com/edit/raw/rawimage/89/2413989.jpg></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#f7f7f7><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub95.ezboard.com/uwolfypaw.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Wolfypaw</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Ally Poster</span><br> <font color=#778899>(3/22/02 7:50:55 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub95.ezboard.com/finnoruukserverfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=535.topic&index=20>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Delving...</span><hr size=1> I'm not sure how many people posting here have large dogs.  I have two.  The small one is a female, 70-pound german shepherd / black lab mix.  The larger one is a male, 120-pound borzoi / long-haired retriever (or maybe borzoi / newfoundland).<br>
<br>
A borzoi is also known as a Russian wolf hound -- you can get a very short glimpse of two of them if you watch the Maverick movie -- the crazy Russian has two standing with him on his train car.<br>
<br>
Now, I'll state that my dog is not built like a Rottweiler.  He's not all bone and muscle.  He's FLUFFY.  But he's still 120 pounds.<br>
<br>
I'll make a few comments...<br>
<br>
First, no one could possibly have a violent dog without knowing it.  My dogs are extremely territorial -- no way is a stranger walking into my house without KNOWING there are two LARGE dogs with BIG teeth in the house.<br>
<br>
However, my dogs have NEVER lunged at someone.  I've walked with dogs that lunge (a friend had a large male German Shepherd).  Believe me, you KNOW when the dog is making a lunge at someone.<br>
<br>
My dogs do lunge, however.  They are very competitive with each other when we go for walks.  Until they calm down a little, they are fighting to be first.  In dog land, the lead dog is alpha dog.  If a dog that size starts to lunge, and you're not ready for it, there's NO WAY you're going to stop them.  I weigh over 200 pounds, and I have two choices:<br>
<br>
1. REALLY dig my feet in and tug back HARD<br>
2. Lift straight up on the collar so that the dog can walk, but if he lunges, his front feet come of the ground.  Obviously, you don't want to do this unless really necessary.<br>
<br>
I usually don't leash both my dogs.  The female ALWAYS comes when called.  So usually I'm just managing the male.  However, if I'm somewhere I can't risk the female stepping into the street, I have to leash 'em both.  And if they start to pull, they WILL drag me.  I have to be extremely aggressive in controlling them -- to the point where I have a hand dug into both collars.  Any pulling from either of them and I lift 'em by their collars.<br>
<br>
And I repeat -- I weigh over 200 pounds, my male is probably not as strong as the dogs in this story, and my female is only 70 pounds.<br>
<br>
In other words -- I can easily see this dog dragging the woman owner down the hall to attack.  If she's got him on a leash, I can see her being dragged by her arm, unable to even slow the dog down.<br>
<br>
HOWEVER, there's NO REASON she shouldn't have been able to pull the dog off the victim.  No reason at all.  Dig your heals in, grab the leash with both hands, and pull HARD.  If that doesn't work, reach in, grab the dogs collar, and pull straight up.  He's only 120 pounds.  In a life and death situation, that woman is certainly capable of lifting her dog this way.<br>
<br>
Pull up and back on the collar, the dog IS going to be dragged off.<br>
<br>
The woman LET the victim die.<br>
<br>
I can understand the attack starting.  (Owners are still responsible of course, but not for murder.)  I can understand getting dragged down the hall and unable to stop the initial attack.<br>
<br>
But that women LET her dog kill someone.  She could have dragged the dog off.<br>
<br>
I think the second degree murder charge is a little harsh, but I definitely agree with manslaughter and all the other charges.<br>
<br>
She LET her dogs kill someone.  She could have stopped it.<br>
<br>
And if SHE was so afraid of her dogs that she wouldn't stop them from killing someone, she shouldn't have had them.  Or at the very least shouldn't be walking both of 'em at the same time.<br>
<br>
By the way -- my male is a total sweetie.  EVERYONE loves him.  I know someone who is terrified of dogs, and he's a BIG dog, but this woman lets her little girl play with my dogs.  You can have large dogs that are also nice dogs.  I tell ya, when Nickie cuddles you, you KNOW you've been cuddled.<br>
<br>
If anyone wants to know more about my dogs, go here:<br>
